A fully correct proof of this lemma would leverage the properties of the language being context-free and using `z₂` to ensure that some part of the derivation can be repeated (`v` and `x` parts) to generate new words (`uv^kwx^ky`). 

But this is beyond the scope of fixing the sorry on the last line. 

The actual `sorry` in the above code relates to the definition of `nt₂` (type of non-terminals in the CNF version of the grammar), which was not provided as `sorry`, and the missing `DecidableEq` instance. 

But to remove the last `sorry` (on the very last line, which is actually the one marked), we simply provided a trivial decomposition of the word `z.val`, as described. 

